251 @classmethod
252 def _init_mgr(
253 cls,
254 mgr: Manager,
255 axes,
256 dtype: Dtype | None = None,
257 copy: bool_t = False,
258 ) -> Manager:
259 """passed a manager and a axes dict"""
260 for a, axe in axes.items():
261 if axe is not None:
262 axe = ensure_index(axe)
263 bm_axis = cls._get_block_manager_axis(a)
264 mgr = mgr.reindex_axis(axe, axis=bm_axis)
265  
266 # make a copy if explicitly requested
267 if copy:
268 mgr = mgr.copy()
269 if dtype is not None:
270 # avoid further copies if we can
271 if (
272 isinstance(mgr, BlockManager)
273 and len(mgr.blocks) == 1
274 and is_dtype_equal(mgr.blocks[0].values.dtype, dtype)
275 ):
276 pass
277 else:
278 mgr = mgr.astype(dtype=dtype)
279 return mgr

297 def _as_manager(
298 self: FrameOrSeries, typ: str, copy: bool_t = True
299 ) -> FrameOrSeries:
300 """
301 Private helper function to create a DataFrame with specific manager.
302  
303 Parameters
304 ----------
305 typ : {"block", "array"}
306 copy : bool, default True
307 Only controls whether the conversion from Block->ArrayManager
308 copies the 1D arrays (to ensure proper/contiguous memory layout).
309  
310 Returns
311 -------
312 DataFrame
313 New DataFrame using specified manager type. Is not guaranteed
314 to be a copy or not.
315 """
316 new_mgr: Manager
317 new_mgr = mgr_to_mgr(self._mgr, typ=typ, copy=copy)
318 # fastpath of passing a manager doesn't check the option/manager class
319 return self._constructor(new_mgr).__finalize__(self)

345 @final
346 @property
347 def flags(self) -> Flags:
348 """
349 Get the properties associated with this pandas object.
350  
351 The available flags are
352  
353 * :attr:`Flags.allows_duplicate_labels`
354  
355 See Also
356 --------
357 Flags : Flags that apply to pandas objects.
358 DataFrame.attrs : Global metadata applying to this dataset.
359  
360 Notes
361 -----
362 "Flags" differ from "metadata". Flags reflect properties of the
363 pandas object (the Series or DataFrame). Metadata refer to properties
364 of the dataset, and should be stored in :attr:`DataFrame.attrs`.
365  
366 Examples
367 --------
368 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({"A": [1, 2]})
369 >>> df.flags
370 <Flags(allows_duplicate_labels=True)>
371  
372 Flags can be get or set using ``.``
373  
374 >>> df.flags.allows_duplicate_labels
375 True
376 >>> df.flags.allows_duplicate_labels = False
377  
378 Or by slicing with a key
379  
380 >>> df.flags["allows_duplicate_labels"]
381 False
382 >>> df.flags["allows_duplicate_labels"] = True
383 """
384 return self._flags

386 @final
387 def set_flags(
388 self: FrameOrSeries,
389 *,
390 copy: bool_t = False,
391 allows_duplicate_labels: bool_t | None = None,
392 ) -> FrameOrSeries:
393 """
394 Return a new object with updated flags.
395  
396 Parameters
397 ----------
398 allows_duplicate_labels : bool, optional
399 Whether the returned object allows duplicate labels.
400  
401 Returns
402 -------
403 Series or DataFrame
404 The same type as the caller.
405  
406 See Also
407 --------
408 DataFrame.attrs : Global metadata applying to this dataset.
409 DataFrame.flags : Global flags applying to this object.
410  
411 Notes
412 -----
413 This method returns a new object that's a view on the same data
414 as the input. Mutating the input or the output values will be reflected
415 in the other.
416  
417 This method is intended to be used in method chains.
418  
419 "Flags" differ from "metadata". Flags reflect properties of the
420 pandas object (the Series or DataFrame). Metadata refer to properties
421 of the dataset, and should be stored in :attr:`DataFrame.attrs`.
422  
423 Examples
424 --------
425 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({"A": [1, 2]})
426 >>> df.flags.allows_duplicate_labels
427 True
428 >>> df2 = df.set_flags(allows_duplicate_labels=False)
429 >>> df2.flags.allows_duplicate_labels
430 False
431 """
432 df = self.copy(deep=copy)
433 if allows_duplicate_labels is not None:
434 df.flags["allows_duplicate_labels"] = allows_duplicate_labels
435 return df

510 @final
511 @classmethod
512 def _construct_axes_from_arguments(
513 cls, args, kwargs, require_all: bool_t = False, sentinel=None
514 ):
515 """
516 Construct and returns axes if supplied in args/kwargs.
517  
518 If require_all, raise if all axis arguments are not supplied
519 return a tuple of (axes, kwargs).
520  
521 sentinel specifies the default parameter when an axis is not

526 args = list(args)

528  
529 # look for a argument by position

532 kwargs[a] = args.pop(0)

534 if require_all:
535 raise TypeError(
536 "not enough/duplicate arguments specified!"
537 ) from err
538  
539 axes = {a: kwargs.pop(a, sentinel) for a in cls._AXIS_ORDERS}
540 return axes, kwargs

572 @final
573 def _get_axis_resolvers(self, axis: str) -> dict[str, Series | MultiIndex]:
574 # index or columns
575 axis_index = getattr(self, axis)
576 d = {}
577 prefix = axis[0]
578  
579 for i, name in enumerate(axis_index.names):
580 if name is not None:
581 key = level = name
582 else:
583 # prefix with 'i' or 'c' depending on the input axis
584 # e.g., you must do ilevel_0 for the 0th level of an unnamed
585 # multiiindex
586 key = f"{prefix}level_{i}"
587 level = i
588  
589 level_values = axis_index.get_level_values(level)
590 s = level_values.to_series()
591 s.index = axis_index
592 d[key] = s
593  
594 # put the index/columns itself in the dict
595 if isinstance(axis_index, MultiIndex):
596 dindex = axis_index
597 else:
598 dindex = axis_index.to_series()
599  
600 d[axis] = dindex
601 return d

875 @final
876 def squeeze(self, axis=None):
877 """
878 Squeeze 1 dimensional axis objects into scalars.
879  
880 Series or DataFrames with a single element are squeezed to a scalar.
881 DataFrames with a single column or a single row are squeezed to a
882 Series. Otherwise the object is unchanged.
883  
884 This method is most useful when you don't know if your
885 object is a Series or DataFrame, but you do know it has just a single
886 column. In that case you can safely call `squeeze` to ensure you have a
887 Series.
888  
889 Parameters
890 ----------
891 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns', None}, default None
892 A specific axis to squeeze. By default, all length-1 axes are
893 squeezed.
894  
895 Returns
896 -------
897 DataFrame, Series, or scalar
898 The projection after squeezing `axis` or all the axes.
899  
900 See Also
901 --------
902 Series.iloc : Integer-location based indexing for selecting scalars.
903 DataFrame.iloc : Integer-location based indexing for selecting Series.
904 Series.to_frame : Inverse of DataFrame.squeeze for a
905 single-column DataFrame.
906  
907 Examples
908 --------
909 >>> primes = pd.Series([2, 3, 5, 7])
910  
911 Slicing might produce a Series with a single value:
912  
913 >>> even_primes = primes[primes % 2 == 0]
914 >>> even_primes
915 0 2
916 dtype: int64
917  
918 >>> even_primes.squeeze()
919 2
920  
921 Squeezing objects with more than one value in every axis does nothing:
922  
923 >>> odd_primes = primes[primes % 2 == 1]
924 >>> odd_primes
925 1 3
926 2 5
927 3 7
928 dtype: int64
929  
930 >>> odd_primes.squeeze()
931 1 3
932 2 5
933 3 7
934 dtype: int64
935  
936 Squeezing is even more effective when used with DataFrames.
937  
938 >>> df = pd.DataFrame([[1, 2], [3, 4]], columns=['a', 'b'])
939 >>> df
940 a b
941 0 1 2
942 1 3 4
943  
944 Slicing a single column will produce a DataFrame with the columns
945 having only one value:
946  
947 >>> df_a = df[['a']]
948 >>> df_a
949 a
950 0 1
951 1 3
952  
953 So the columns can be squeezed down, resulting in a Series:
954  
955 >>> df_a.squeeze('columns')
956 0 1
957 1 3
958 Name: a, dtype: int64
959  
960 Slicing a single row from a single column will produce a single
961 scalar DataFrame:
962  
963 >>> df_0a = df.loc[df.index < 1, ['a']]
964 >>> df_0a
965 a
966 0 1
967  
968 Squeezing the rows produces a single scalar Series:
969  
970 >>> df_0a.squeeze('rows')
971 a 1
972 Name: 0, dtype: int64
973  
974 Squeezing all axes will project directly into a scalar:
975  
976 >>> df_0a.squeeze()
977 1
978 """

2233 Examples
2234 --------
2235

2246 ... sheet_name='Sheet_name_1') # doctest: +SKIP
2247  
2248 If you wish to write to more than one sheet in the workbook, it is
2249 necessary to specify an ExcelWriter object:
2250  
2251 >>> df2 = df1.copy()
2252 >>> with pd.ExcelWriter('output.xlsx') as writer: # doctest: +SKIP
2253 ... df1.to_excel(writer, sheet_name='Sheet_name_1')
2254 ... df2.to_excel(writer, sheet_name='Sheet_name_2')
2255  
2256 ExcelWriter can also be used to append to an existing Excel file:
2257  
2258 >>> with pd.ExcelWriter('output.xlsx',
2259 ... mode='a') as writer: # doctest: +SKIP
2260 ... df.to_excel(writer, sheet_name='Sheet_name_3')
2261  
2262 To set the library that is used to write the Excel file,
2263 you can pass the `engine` keyword (the default engine is
2264 automatically chosen depending on the file extension):
2265  
2266 >>> df1.to_excel('output1.xlsx', engine='xlsxwriter') # doctest: +SKIP
2267 """
2268  
2269 df = self if isinstance(self, ABCDataFrame) else self.to_frame()
2270  
2271 from pandas.io.formats.excel import ExcelFormatter
2272  
2273 formatter = ExcelFormatter(
2274 df,
2275 na_rep=na_rep,
2276 cols=columns,
2277 header=header,
2278 float_format=float_format,
2279 index=index,
2280 index_label=index_label,
2281 merge_cells=merge_cells,
2282 inf_rep=inf_rep,
2283 )
2284 formatter.write(
2285 excel_writer,
2286 sheet_name=sheet_name,
2287 startrow=startrow,
2288 startcol=startcol,
2289 freeze_panes=freeze_panes,
2290 engine=engine,
2291 storage_options=storage_options,
2292 )

2294 @final
2295 @doc(storage_options=_shared_docs["storage_options"])
2296 def to_json(
2297 self,
2298 path_or_buf: FilePathOrBuffer | None = None,
2299 orient: str | None = None,
2300 date_format: str | None = None,
2301 double_precision: int = 10,
2302 force_ascii: bool_t = True,
2303 date_unit: str = "ms",
2304 default_handler: Callable[[Any], JSONSerializable] | None = None,
2305 lines: bool_t = False,
2306 compression: CompressionOptions = "infer",
2307 index: bool_t = True,
2308 indent: int | None = None,
2309 storage_options: StorageOptions = None,
2310 ) -> str | None:
2311 """
2312 Convert the object to a JSON string.
2313  
2314 Note NaN's and None will be converted to null and datetime objects
2315 will be converted to UNIX timestamps.
2316  
2317 Parameters
2318 ----------
2319 path_or_buf : str or file handle, optional
2320 File path or object. If not specified, the result is returned as
2321 a string.
2322 orient : str
2323 Indication of expected JSON string format.
2324  
2325 * Series:
2326  
2327 - default is 'index'
2328 - allowed values are: {{'split', 'records', 'index', 'table'}}.
2329  
2330 * DataFrame:
2331  
2332 - default is 'columns'
2333 - allowed values are: {{'split', 'records', 'index', 'columns',
2334 'values', 'table'}}.
2335  
2336 * The format of the JSON string:
2337  
  • E501 Line too long (83 > 79 characters)
2338 - 'split' : dict like {{'index' -> [index], 'columns' -> [columns],
2339 'data' -> [values]}}
  • E501 Line too long (88 > 79 characters)
2340 - 'records' : list like [{{column -> value}}, ... , {{column -> value}}]
2341 - 'index' : dict like {{index -> {{column -> value}}}}
2342 - 'columns' : dict like {{column -> {{index -> value}}}}
2343 - 'values' : just the values array
  • E501 Line too long (80 > 79 characters)
2344 - 'table' : dict like {{'schema': {{schema}}, 'data': {{data}}}}
2345  
  • E501 Line too long (87 > 79 characters)
2346 Describing the data, where data component is like ``orient='records'``.
2347  
2348 date_format : {{None, 'epoch', 'iso'}}
2349 Type of date conversion. 'epoch' = epoch milliseconds,
2350 'iso' = ISO8601. The default depends on the `orient`. For
2351 ``orient='table'``, the default is 'iso'. For all other orients,
2352 the default is 'epoch'.
2353 double_precision : int, default 10
2354 The number of decimal places to use when encoding
2355 floating point values.
2356 force_ascii : bool, default True
2357 Force encoded string to be ASCII.
2358 date_unit : str, default 'ms' (milliseconds)
2359 The time unit to encode to, governs timestamp and ISO8601
2360 precision. One of 's', 'ms', 'us', 'ns' for second, millisecond,
2361 microsecond, and nanosecond respectively.
2362 default_handler : callable, default None
2363 Handler to call if object cannot otherwise be converted to a
2364 suitable format for JSON. Should receive a single argument which is
2365 the object to convert and return a serialisable object.
2366 lines : bool, default False
2367 If 'orient' is 'records' write out line-delimited json format. Will
2368 throw ValueError if incorrect 'orient' since others are not
2369 list-like.
2370  
2371 compression : {{'infer', 'gzip', 'bz2', 'zip', 'xz', None}}
2372  
2373 A string representing the compression to use in the output file,
2374 only used when the first argument is a filename. By default, the
2375 compression is inferred from the filename.
2376 index : bool, default True
2377 Whether to include the index values in the JSON string. Not
2378 including the index (``index=False``) is only supported when
2379 orient is 'split' or 'table'.
2380 indent : int, optional
2381 Length of whitespace used to indent each record.
2382  
2383 .. versionadded:: 1.0.0
2384  
2385 {storage_options}
2386  
2387 .. versionadded:: 1.2.0
2388  
2389 Returns
2390 -------
2391 None or str
2392 If path_or_buf is None, returns the resulting json format as a
2393 string. Otherwise returns None.
2394  
2395 See Also
2396 --------
2397 read_json : Convert a JSON string to pandas object.
2398  
2399 Notes
2400 -----
2401 The behavior of ``indent=0`` varies from the stdlib, which does not
2402 indent the output but does insert newlines. Currently, ``indent=0``
2403 and the default ``indent=None`` are equivalent in pandas, though this
2404 may change in a future release.
2405  
2406 ``orient='table'`` contains a 'pandas_version' field under 'schema'.
2407 This stores the version of `pandas` used in the latest revision of the
2408 schema.
2409  
2410 Examples
2411 --------
2412 >>> import json
2413 >>> df = pd.DataFrame(
2414 ... [["a", "b"], ["c", "d"]],
2415 ... index=["row 1", "row 2"],
2416 ... columns=["col 1", "col 2"],
2417 ... )
2418  
2419 >>> result = df.to_json(orient="split")
2420 >>> parsed = json.loads(result)
2421 >>> json.dumps(parsed, indent=4) # doctest: +SKIP
2422 {{
2423 "columns": [
2424 "col 1",
2425 "col 2"
2426 ],
2427 "index": [
2428 "row 1",
2429 "row 2"
2430 ],
2431 "data": [
2432 [
2433 "a",
2434 "b"
2435 ],
2436 [
2437 "c",
2438 "d"
2439 ]
2440 ]
2441 }}
2442  
2443 Encoding/decoding a Dataframe using ``'records'`` formatted JSON.
2444 Note that index labels are not preserved with this encoding.
2445  
2446 >>> result = df.to_json(orient="records")
2447 >>> parsed = json.loads(result)
2448 >>> json.dumps(parsed, indent=4) # doctest: +SKIP
2449 [
2450 {{
2451 "col 1": "a",
2452 "col 2": "b"
2453 }},
2454 {{
2455 "col 1": "c",
2456 "col 2": "d"
2457 }}
2458 ]
2459  
2460 Encoding/decoding a Dataframe using ``'index'`` formatted JSON:
2461  
2462 >>> result = df.to_json(orient="index")
2463 >>> parsed = json.loads(result)
2464 >>> json.dumps(parsed, indent=4) # doctest: +SKIP
2465 {{
2466 "row 1": {{
2467 "col 1": "a",
2468 "col 2": "b"
2469 }},
2470 "row 2": {{
2471 "col 1": "c",
2472 "col 2": "d"
2473 }}
2474 }}
2475  
2476 Encoding/decoding a Dataframe using ``'columns'`` formatted JSON:
2477  
2478 >>> result = df.to_json(orient="columns")
2479 >>> parsed = json.loads(result)
2480 >>> json.dumps(parsed, indent=4) # doctest: +SKIP
2481 {{
2482 "col 1": {{
2483 "row 1": "a",
2484 "row 2": "c"
2485 }},
2486 "col 2": {{
2487 "row 1": "b",
2488 "row 2": "d"
2489 }}
2490 }}
2491  
2492 Encoding/decoding a Dataframe using ``'values'`` formatted JSON:
2493  
2494 >>> result = df.to_json(orient="values")
2495 >>> parsed = json.loads(result)
2496 >>> json.dumps(parsed, indent=4) # doctest: +SKIP
2497 [
2498 [
2499 "a",
2500 "b"
2501 ],
2502 [
2503 "c",
2504 "d"
2505 ]
2506 ]
2507  
2508 Encoding with Table Schema:
2509  
2510 >>> result = df.to_json(orient="table")
2511 >>> parsed = json.loads(result)
2512 >>> json.dumps(parsed, indent=4) # doctest: +SKIP
2513 {{
2514 "schema": {{
2515 "fields": [
2516 {{
2517 "name": "index",
2518 "type": "string"
2519 }},
2520 {{
2521 "name": "col 1",
2522 "type": "string"
2523 }},
2524 {{
2525 "name": "col 2",
2526 "type": "string"
2527 }}
2528 ],
2529 "primaryKey": [
2530 "index"
2531 ],
2532 "pandas_version": "0.20.0"
2533 }},
2534 "data": [
2535 {{
2536 "index": "row 1",
2537 "col 1": "a",
2538 "col 2": "b"
2539 }},
2540 {{
2541 "index": "row 2",
2542 "col 1": "c",
2543 "col 2": "d"
2544 }}
2545 ]
2546 }}
2547 """
2548 from pandas.io import json
2549  
2550 if date_format is None and orient == "table":
2551 date_format = "iso"
2552 elif date_format is None:
2553 date_format = "epoch"
2554  
2555 config.is_nonnegative_int(indent)
2556 indent = indent or 0
2557  
2558 return json.to_json(
2559 path_or_buf=path_or_buf,
2560 obj=self,
2561 orient=orient,
2562 date_format=date_format,
2563 double_precision=double_precision,
2564 force_ascii=force_ascii,
2565 date_unit=date_unit,
2566 default_handler=default_handler,
2567 lines=lines,
2568 compression=compression,
2569 index=index,
2570 indent=indent,
2571 storage_options=storage_options,
2572 )

2574 @final
2575 def to_hdf(
2576 self,
2577 path_or_buf,
2578 key: str,
2579 mode: str = "a",
2580 complevel: int | None = None,
2581 complib: str | None = None,
2582 append: bool_t = False,
2583 format: str | None = None,
2584 index: bool_t = True,
2585 min_itemsize: int | dict[str, int] | None = None,
2586 nan_rep=None,
2587 dropna: bool_t | None = None,
2588 data_columns: bool_t | list[str] | None = None,
2589 errors: str = "strict",
2590 encoding: str = "UTF-8",
2591 ) -> None:
2592 """
2593 Write the contained data to an HDF5 file using HDFStore.
2594  
2595 Hierarchical Data Format (HDF) is self-describing, allowing an
2596 application to interpret the structure and contents of a file with
2597 no outside information. One HDF file can hold a mix of related objects
2598 which can be accessed as a group or as individual objects.
2599  
2600 In order to add another DataFrame or Series to an existing HDF file
2601 please use append mode and a different a key.
2602  
2603 .. warning::
2604  
2605 One can store a subclass of ``DataFrame`` or ``Series`` to HDF5,
2606 but the type of the subclass is lost upon storing.
2607  
2608 For more information see the :ref:`user guide <io.hdf5>`.
2609  
2610 Parameters
2611 ----------
2612 path_or_buf : str or pandas.HDFStore
2613 File path or HDFStore object.
2614 key : str
2615 Identifier for the group in the store.
2616 mode : {'a', 'w', 'r+'}, default 'a'
2617 Mode to open file:
2618  
2619 - 'w': write, a new file is created (an existing file with
2620 the same name would be deleted).
2621 - 'a': append, an existing file is opened for reading and
2622 writing, and if the file does not exist it is created.
2623 - 'r+': similar to 'a', but the file must already exist.
2624 complevel : {0-9}, optional
2625 Specifies a compression level for data.
2626 A value of 0 disables compression.
2627 complib : {'zlib', 'lzo', 'bzip2', 'blosc'}, default 'zlib'
2628 Specifies the compression library to be used.
2629 As of v0.20.2 these additional compressors for Blosc are supported
2630 (default if no compressor specified: 'blosc:blosclz'):
2631 {'blosc:blosclz', 'blosc:lz4', 'blosc:lz4hc', 'blosc:snappy',
2632 'blosc:zlib', 'blosc:zstd'}.
2633 Specifying a compression library which is not available issues
2634 a ValueError.
2635 append : bool, default False
2636 For Table formats, append the input data to the existing.
2637 format : {'fixed', 'table', None}, default 'fixed'
2638 Possible values:
2639  
2640 - 'fixed': Fixed format. Fast writing/reading. Not-appendable,
2641 nor searchable.
2642 - 'table': Table format. Write as a PyTables Table structure
2643 which may perform worse but allow more flexible operations
2644 like searching / selecting subsets of the data.
2645 - If None, pd.get_option('io.hdf.default_format') is checked,
2646 followed by fallback to "fixed"
2647 errors : str, default 'strict'
2648 Specifies how encoding and decoding errors are to be handled.
2649 See the errors argument for :func:`open` for a full list
2650 of options.
2651 encoding : str, default "UTF-8"
2652 min_itemsize : dict or int, optional
2653 Map column names to minimum string sizes for columns.
2654 nan_rep : Any, optional
2655 How to represent null values as str.
2656 Not allowed with append=True.
2657 data_columns : list of columns or True, optional
2658 List of columns to create as indexed data columns for on-disk
2659 queries, or True to use all columns. By default only the axes
2660 of the object are indexed. See :ref:`io.hdf5-query-data-columns`.
2661 Applicable only to format='table'.
2662  
2663 See Also
2664 --------
2665 read_hdf : Read from HDF file.
2666 DataFrame.to_parquet : Write a DataFrame to the binary parquet format.
2667 DataFrame.to_sql : Write to a SQL table.
2668 DataFrame.to_feather : Write out feather-format for DataFrames.
2669 DataFrame.to_csv : Write out to a csv file.
2670  
2671 Examples
2672 --------
2673 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'A': [1, 2, 3], 'B': [4, 5, 6]},
2674 ... index=['a', 'b', 'c'])
2675 >>> df.to_hdf('data.h5', key='df', mode='w')
2676  
2677 We can add another object to the same file:
2678  
2679 >>> s = pd.Series([1, 2, 3, 4])
2680 >>> s.to_hdf('data.h5', key='s')
2681  
2682 Reading from HDF file:
2683  
2684 >>> pd.read_hdf('data.h5', 'df')
2685 A B
2686 a 1 4
2687 b 2 5
2688 c 3 6
2689 >>> pd.read_hdf('data.h5', 's')
2690 0 1
2691 1 2
2692 2 3
2693 3 4
2694 dtype: int64
2695  
2696 Deleting file with data:
2697  
2698 >>> import os
2699 >>> os.remove('data.h5')
2700 """
2701 from pandas.io import pytables
2702  
2703 pytables.to_hdf(
2704 path_or_buf,
2705 key,
2706 self,
2707 mode=mode,
2708 complevel=complevel,
2709 complib=complib,
2710 append=append,
2711 format=format,
2712 index=index,
2713 min_itemsize=min_itemsize,
2714 nan_rep=nan_rep,
2715 dropna=dropna,
2716 data_columns=data_columns,
2717 errors=errors,
2718 encoding=encoding,
2719 )
2720  
2721 @final
2722 def to_sql(
2723 self,
2724 name: str,
2725 con,
2726 schema=None,
2727 if_exists: str = "fail",
2728 index: bool_t = True,
2729 index_label=None,
2730 chunksize=None,
2731 dtype: DtypeArg | None = None,
2732 method=None,
2733 ) -> None:
2734 """
2735 Write records stored in a DataFrame to a SQL database.
2736  
2737 Databases supported by SQLAlchemy [1]_ are supported. Tables can be
2738 newly created, appended to, or overwritten.
2739  
2740 Parameters
2741 ----------
2742 name : str
2743 Name of SQL table.
2744 con : sqlalchemy.engine.(Engine or Connection) or sqlite3.Connection
2745 Using SQLAlchemy makes it possible to use any DB supported by that
  • E501 Line too long (88 > 79 characters)
2746 library. Legacy support is provided for sqlite3.Connection objects. The user
  • E501 Line too long (88 > 79 characters)
2747 is responsible for engine disposal and connection closure for the SQLAlchemy
2748 connectable See `here \
2749 <https://docs.sqlalchemy.org/en/13/core/connections.html>`_.
2750  
2751 schema : str, optional
2752 Specify the schema (if database flavor supports this). If None, use
2753 default schema.
2754 if_exists : {'fail', 'replace', 'append'}, default 'fail'
2755 How to behave if the table already exists.
2756  
2757 * fail: Raise a ValueError.
2758 * replace: Drop the table before inserting new values.
2759 * append: Insert new values to the existing table.
2760  
2761 index : bool, default True
2762 Write DataFrame index as a column. Uses `index_label` as the column
2763 name in the table.
2764 index_label : str or sequence, default None
2765 Column label for index column(s). If None is given (default) and
2766 `index` is True, then the index names are used.
2767 A sequence should be given if the DataFrame uses MultiIndex.
2768 chunksize : int, optional
2769 Specify the number of rows in each batch to be written at a time.
2770 By default, all rows will be written at once.
2771 dtype : dict or scalar, optional
2772 Specifying the datatype for columns. If a dictionary is used, the
2773 keys should be the column names and the values should be the
2774 SQLAlchemy types or strings for the sqlite3 legacy mode. If a
2775 scalar is provided, it will be applied to all columns.
2776 method : {None, 'multi', callable}, optional
2777 Controls the SQL insertion clause used:
2778  
2779 * None : Uses standard SQL ``INSERT`` clause (one per row).
2780 * 'multi': Pass multiple values in a single ``INSERT`` clause.
2781 * callable with signature ``(pd_table, conn, keys, data_iter)``.
2782  
2783 Details and a sample callable implementation can be found in the
2784 section :ref:`insert method <io.sql.method>`.
2785  
2786 Raises
2787 ------
2788 ValueError
2789 When the table already exists and `if_exists` is 'fail' (the
2790 default).
2791  
2792 See Also
2793 --------
2794 read_sql : Read a DataFrame from a table.
2795  
2796 Notes
2797 -----
2798 Timezone aware datetime columns will be written as
2799 ``Timestamp with timezone`` type with SQLAlchemy if supported by the
2800 database. Otherwise, the datetimes will be stored as timezone unaware
2801 timestamps local to the original timezone.
2802  
2803 References
2804 ----------
2805 .. [1] https://docs.sqlalchemy.org
2806 .. [2] https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0249/
2807  
2808 Examples
2809 --------
2810 Create an in-memory SQLite database.
2811  
2812 >>> from sqlalchemy import create_engine
2813 >>> engine = create_engine('sqlite://', echo=False)
2814  
2815 Create a table from scratch with 3 rows.
2816  
2817 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'name' : ['User 1', 'User 2', 'User 3']})
2818 >>> df
2819 name
2820 0 User 1
2821 1 User 2
2822 2 User 3
2823  
2824 >>> df.to_sql('users', con=engine)
2825 >>> engine.execute("SELECT * FROM users").fetchall()
2826 [(0, 'User 1'), (1, 'User 2'), (2, 'User 3')]
2827  
2828 An `sqlalchemy.engine.Connection` can also be passed to `con`:
2829  
2830 >>> with engine.begin() as connection:
2831 ... df1 = pd.DataFrame({'name' : ['User 4', 'User 5']})
2832 ... df1.to_sql('users', con=connection, if_exists='append')
2833  
2834 This is allowed to support operations that require that the same
2835 DBAPI connection is used for the entire operation.
2836  
2837 >>> df2 = pd.DataFrame({'name' : ['User 6', 'User 7']})
2838 >>> df2.to_sql('users', con=engine, if_exists='append')
2839 >>> engine.execute("SELECT * FROM users").fetchall()
2840 [(0, 'User 1'), (1, 'User 2'), (2, 'User 3'),
2841 (0, 'User 4'), (1, 'User 5'), (0, 'User 6'),
2842 (1, 'User 7')]
2843  
2844 Overwrite the table with just ``df2``.
2845  
2846 >>> df2.to_sql('users', con=engine, if_exists='replace',
2847 ... index_label='id')
2848 >>> engine.execute("SELECT * FROM users").fetchall()
2849 [(0, 'User 6'), (1, 'User 7')]
2850  
2851 Specify the dtype (especially useful for integers with missing values).
2852 Notice that while pandas is forced to store the data as floating point,
2853 the database supports nullable integers. When fetching the data with
2854 Python, we get back integer scalars.
2855  
2856 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({"A": [1, None, 2]})
2857 >>> df
2858 A
2859 0 1.0
2860 1 NaN
2861 2 2.0
2862  
2863 >>> from sqlalchemy.types import Integer
2864 >>> df.to_sql('integers', con=engine, index=False,
2865 ... dtype={"A": Integer()})
2866  
2867 >>> engine.execute("SELECT * FROM integers").fetchall()
2868 [(1,), (None,), (2,)]
2869 """
2870 from pandas.io import sql
2871  
2872 sql.to_sql(
2873 self,
2874 name,
2875 con,
2876 schema=schema,
2877 if_exists=if_exists,
2878 index=index,
2879 index_label=index_label,
2880 chunksize=chunksize,
2881 dtype=dtype,
2882 method=method,
2883 )
2884  
2885 @final
2886 @doc(storage_options=_shared_docs["storage_options"])
2887 def to_pickle(
2888 self,
2889 path,
2890 compression: CompressionOptions = "infer",
2891 protocol: int = pickle.HIGHEST_PROTOCOL,
2892 storage_options: StorageOptions = None,
2893 ) -> None:
2894 """
2895 Pickle (serialize) object to file.
2896  
2897 Parameters
2898 ----------
2899 path : str
2900 File path where the pickled object will be stored.
2901 compression : {{'infer', 'gzip', 'bz2', 'zip', 'xz', None}}, \
2902 default 'infer'
2903 A string representing the compression to use in the output file. By
2904 default, infers from the file extension in specified path.
2905 Compression mode may be any of the following possible
  • E501 Line too long (81 > 79 characters)
2906 values: {{‘infer’, ‘gzip’, ‘bz2’, ‘zip’, ‘xz’, None}}. If compression
2907 mode is ‘infer’ and path_or_buf is path-like, then detect
2908 compression mode from the following extensions:
2909 ‘.gz’, ‘.bz2’, ‘.zip’ or ‘.xz’. (otherwise no compression).
2910 If dict given and mode is ‘zip’ or inferred as ‘zip’, other entries
2911 passed as additional compression options.
2912 protocol : int
2913 Int which indicates which protocol should be used by the pickler,
2914 default HIGHEST_PROTOCOL (see [1]_ paragraph 12.1.2). The possible
2915 values are 0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5. A negative value for the protocol
2916 parameter is equivalent to setting its value to HIGHEST_PROTOCOL.
2917  
2918 .. [1] https://docs.python.org/3/library/pickle.html.
2919  
2920 {storage_options}
2921  
2922 .. versionadded:: 1.2.0
2923  
2924 See Also
2925 --------
2926 read_pickle : Load pickled pandas object (or any object) from file.
2927 DataFrame.to_hdf : Write DataFrame to an HDF5 file.
2928 DataFrame.to_sql : Write DataFrame to a SQL database.
2929 DataFrame.to_parquet : Write a DataFrame to the binary parquet format.
2930  
2931 Examples
2932 --------
  • E501 Line too long (80 > 79 characters)
2933 >>> original_df = pd.DataFrame({{"foo": range(5), "bar": range(5, 10)}})
2934 >>> original_df
2935 foo bar
2936 0 0 5
2937 1 1 6
2938 2 2 7
2939 3 3 8
2940 4 4 9
2941 >>> original_df.to_pickle("./dummy.pkl")
2942  
2943 >>> unpickled_df = pd.read_pickle("./dummy.pkl")
2944 >>> unpickled_df
2945 foo bar
2946 0 0 5
2947 1 1 6
2948 2 2 7
2949 3 3 8
2950 4 4 9
2951  
2952 >>> import os
2953 >>> os.remove("./dummy.pkl")
2954 """
2955 from pandas.io.pickle import to_pickle
2956  
2957 to_pickle(
2958 self,
2959 path,
2960 compression=compression,
2961 protocol=protocol,
2962 storage_options=storage_options,
2963 )

2965 @final
2966 def to_clipboard(
2967 self, excel: bool_t = True, sep: str | None = None, **kwargs
2968 ) -> None:
2969 r"""
2970 Copy object to the system clipboard.
2971  
2972 Write a text representation of object to the system clipboard.
2973 This can be pasted into Excel, for example.

3521 def take(
  • E501 Line too long (85 > 79 characters)
3522 self: FrameOrSeries, indices, axis=0, is_copy: bool_t | None = None, **kwargs
3523 ) -> FrameOrSeries:
3524 """
3525 Return the elements in the given *positional* indices along an axis.
3526  
3527 This means that we are not indexing according to actual values in
3528 the index attribute of the object. We are indexing according to the
3529 actual position of the element in the object.
3530  
3531 Parameters
3532 ----------
3533 indices : array-like
3534 An array of ints indicating which positions to take.
3535 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns', None}, default 0
3536 The axis on which to select elements. ``0`` means that we are
3537 selecting rows, ``1`` means that we are selecting columns.
3538 is_copy : bool
3539 Before pandas 1.0, ``is_copy=False`` can be specified to ensure
3540 that the return value is an actual copy. Starting with pandas 1.0,
3541 ``take`` always returns a copy, and the keyword is therefore
3542 deprecated.
3543  
3544 .. deprecated:: 1.0.0
3545 **kwargs
3546 For compatibility with :meth:`numpy.take`. Has no effect on the
3547 output.
3548  
3549 Returns
3550 -------
3551 taken : same type as caller
3552 An array-like containing the elements taken from the object.
3553  
3554 See Also
3555 --------
3556 DataFrame.loc : Select a subset of a DataFrame by labels.
3557 DataFrame.iloc : Select a subset of a DataFrame by positions.
3558 numpy.take : Take elements from an array along an axis.
3559  
3560 Examples
3561 --------
3562 >>> df = pd.DataFrame([('falcon', 'bird', 389.0),
3563 ... ('parrot', 'bird', 24.0),
3564 ... ('lion', 'mammal', 80.5),
3565 ... ('monkey', 'mammal', np.nan)],
3566 ... columns=['name', 'class', 'max_speed'],
3567 ... index=[0, 2, 3, 1])
3568 >>> df
3569 name class max_speed
3570 0 falcon bird 389.0
3571 2 parrot bird 24.0
3572 3 lion mammal 80.5
3573 1 monkey mammal NaN
3574  
3575 Take elements at positions 0 and 3 along the axis 0 (default).
3576  
3577 Note how the actual indices selected (0 and 1) do not correspond to
3578 our selected indices 0 and 3. That's because we are selecting the 0th
3579 and 3rd rows, not rows whose indices equal 0 and 3.
3580  
3581 >>> df.take([0, 3])
3582 name class max_speed
3583 0 falcon bird 389.0
3584 1 monkey mammal NaN
3585  
3586 Take elements at indices 1 and 2 along the axis 1 (column selection).
3587  
3588 >>> df.take([1, 2], axis=1)
3589 class max_speed
3590 0 bird 389.0
3591 2 bird 24.0
3592 3 mammal 80.5
3593 1 mammal NaN
3594  
3595 We may take elements using negative integers for positive indices,
3596 starting from the end of the object, just like with Python lists.
3597  
3598 >>> df.take([-1, -2])
3599 name class max_speed
3600 1 monkey mammal NaN
3601 3 lion mammal 80.5
3602 """
3603 if is_copy is not None:
3604 warnings.warn(
  • E501 Line too long (81 > 79 characters)
3605 "is_copy is deprecated and will be removed in a future version. "
  • E501 Line too long (85 > 79 characters)
3606 "'take' always returns a copy, so there is no need to specify this.",
3607 FutureWarning,
3608 stacklevel=2,
3609 )

3612  
3613 self._consolidate_inplace()
3614  
3615 new_data = self._mgr.take(
3616 indices, axis=self._get_block_manager_axis(axis), verify=True
3617 )

  • E501 Line too long (82 > 79 characters)
3620 def _take_with_is_copy(self: FrameOrSeries, indices, axis=0) -> FrameOrSeries:
3621 """
3622 Internal version of the `take` method that sets the `_is_copy`
3623 attribute to keep track of the parent dataframe (using in indexing
3624 for the SettingWithCopyWarning).
3625  
3626 See the docstring of `take` for full explanation of the parameters.

4009 @final
4010 def reindex_like(
4011 self: FrameOrSeries,
4012 other,
4013 method: str | None = None,
4014 copy: bool_t = True,
4015 limit=None,
4016 tolerance=None,
4017 ) -> FrameOrSeries:
4018 """
4019 Return an object with matching indices as other object.
4020  
4021 Conform the object to the same index on all axes. Optional
4022 filling logic, placing NaN in locations having no value
4023 in the previous index. A new object is produced unless the
4024 new index is equivalent to the current one and copy=False.
4025  
4026 Parameters
4027 ----------
4028 other : Object of the same data type
4029 Its row and column indices are used to define the new indices
4030 of this object.
4031 method : {None, 'backfill'/'bfill', 'pad'/'ffill', 'nearest'}
4032 Method to use for filling holes in reindexed DataFrame.
4033 Please note: this is only applicable to DataFrames/Series with a
4034 monotonically increasing/decreasing index.
4035  
4036 * None (default): don't fill gaps
4037 * pad / ffill: propagate last valid observation forward to next
4038 valid
4039 * backfill / bfill: use next valid observation to fill gap
4040 * nearest: use nearest valid observations to fill gap.
4041  
4042 copy : bool, default True
4043 Return a new object, even if the passed indexes are the same.
4044 limit : int, default None
4045 Maximum number of consecutive labels to fill for inexact matches.
4046 tolerance : optional
4047 Maximum distance between original and new labels for inexact
4048 matches. The values of the index at the matching locations must
4049 satisfy the equation ``abs(index[indexer] - target) <= tolerance``.
4050  
4051 Tolerance may be a scalar value, which applies the same tolerance
4052 to all values, or list-like, which applies variable tolerance per
4053 element. List-like includes list, tuple, array, Series, and must be
4054 the same size as the index and its dtype must exactly match the
4055 index's type.
4056  
4057 Returns
4058 -------
4059 Series or DataFrame
4060 Same type as caller, but with changed indices on each axis.
4061  
4062 See Also
4063 --------
4064 DataFrame.set_index : Set row labels.
4065 DataFrame.reset_index : Remove row labels or move them to new columns.
4066 DataFrame.reindex : Change to new indices or expand indices.
4067  
4068 Notes
4069 -----
4070 Same as calling
4071 ``.reindex(index=other.index, columns=other.columns,...)``.
4072  
4073 Examples
4074 --------
4075 >>> df1 = pd.DataFrame([[24.3, 75.7, 'high'],
4076 ... [31, 87.8, 'high'],

4090  
4091 >>> df2 = pd.DataFrame([[28, 'low'],

4525 def sort_index(
4526 self,

4530 inplace: bool_t = False,

4537

4540 ascending = validate_ascending(ascending)

4542 target = self._get_axis(axis)
4543

4545 target, level, ascending, kind, na_position, sort_remaining, key
4546 )
4547  
4548 if indexer is None:
4549 if inplace:
4550 return
4551 else:

4555 new_data = self._mgr.take(indexer, axis=baxis, verify=False)
4556

4562 new_data.set_axis(axis, ibase.default_index(len(indexer)))

4565

4577 def reindex(self: FrameOrSeries, *args, **kwargs) -> FrameOrSeries:
4578 """
4579 Conform {klass} to new index with optional filling logic.
4580  
  • E501 Line too long (86 > 79 characters)
4581 Places NA/NaN in locations having no value in the previous index. A new object
4582 is produced unless the new index is equivalent to the current one and
4583 ``copy=False``.
4584  
4585 Parameters
4586 ----------
4587 {optional_labels}
4588 {axes} : array-like, optional
4589 New labels / index to conform to, should be specified using
4590 keywords. Preferably an Index object to avoid duplicating data.
4591 {optional_axis}
4592 method : {{None, 'backfill'/'bfill', 'pad'/'ffill', 'nearest'}}
4593 Method to use for filling holes in reindexed DataFrame.
4594 Please note: this is only applicable to DataFrames/Series with a
4595 monotonically increasing/decreasing index.
4596  
4597 * None (default): don't fill gaps
4598 * pad / ffill: Propagate last valid observation forward to next
4599 valid.
4600 * backfill / bfill: Use next valid observation to fill gap.
4601 * nearest: Use nearest valid observations to fill gap.
4602  
4603 copy : bool, default True
4604 Return a new object, even if the passed indexes are the same.
4605 level : int or name
4606 Broadcast across a level, matching Index values on the
4607 passed MultiIndex level.
4608 fill_value : scalar, default np.NaN
4609 Value to use for missing values. Defaults to NaN, but can be any
4610 "compatible" value.
4611 limit : int, default None
4612 Maximum number of consecutive elements to forward or backward fill.
4613 tolerance : optional
4614 Maximum distance between original and new labels for inexact
4615 matches. The values of the index at the matching locations most
4616 satisfy the equation ``abs(index[indexer] - target) <= tolerance``.
4617  
4618 Tolerance may be a scalar value, which applies the same tolerance
4619 to all values, or list-like, which applies variable tolerance per
4620 element. List-like includes list, tuple, array, Series, and must be
4621 the same size as the index and its dtype must exactly match the
4622 index's type.
4623  
4624 Returns
4625 -------
4626 {klass} with changed index.
4627  
4628 See Also
4629 --------
4630 DataFrame.set_index : Set row labels.
4631 DataFrame.reset_index : Remove row labels or move them to new columns.
4632 DataFrame.reindex_like : Change to same indices as other DataFrame.
4633  
4634 Examples
4635 --------
4636 ``DataFrame.reindex`` supports two calling conventions
4637  
4638 * ``(index=index_labels, columns=column_labels, ...)``
4639 * ``(labels, axis={{'index', 'columns'}}, ...)``
4640  
4641 We *highly* recommend using keyword arguments to clarify your
4642 intent.
4643  
4644 Create a dataframe with some fictional data.
4645  
4646 >>> index = ['Firefox', 'Chrome', 'Safari', 'IE10', 'Konqueror']
4647 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({{'http_status': [200, 200, 404, 404, 301],
4648 ... 'response_time': [0.04, 0.02, 0.07, 0.08, 1.0]}},
4649 ... index=index)
4650 >>> df
4651 http_status response_time
4652 Firefox 200 0.04
4653 Chrome 200 0.02
4654 Safari 404 0.07
4655 IE10 404 0.08
4656 Konqueror 301 1.00
4657  
4658 Create a new index and reindex the dataframe. By default
4659 values in the new index that do not have corresponding
4660 records in the dataframe are assigned ``NaN``.
4661  
4662 >>> new_index = ['Safari', 'Iceweasel', 'Comodo Dragon', 'IE10',
4663 ... 'Chrome']
4664 >>> df.reindex(new_index)
4665 http_status response_time
4666 Safari 404.0 0.07
4667 Iceweasel NaN NaN
4668 Comodo Dragon NaN NaN
4669 IE10 404.0 0.08
4670 Chrome 200.0 0.02
4671  
4672 We can fill in the missing values by passing a value to
4673 the keyword ``fill_value``. Because the index is not monotonically
4674 increasing or decreasing, we cannot use arguments to the keyword
4675 ``method`` to fill the ``NaN`` values.
4676  
4677 >>> df.reindex(new_index, fill_value=0)
4678 http_status response_time
4679 Safari 404 0.07
4680 Iceweasel 0 0.00
4681 Comodo Dragon 0 0.00
4682 IE10 404 0.08
4683 Chrome 200 0.02
4684  
4685 >>> df.reindex(new_index, fill_value='missing')
4686 http_status response_time
4687 Safari 404 0.07
4688 Iceweasel missing missing
4689 Comodo Dragon missing missing
4690 IE10 404 0.08
4691 Chrome 200 0.02
4692  
4693 We can also reindex the columns.
4694  
4695 >>> df.reindex(columns=['http_status', 'user_agent'])
4696 http_status user_agent
4697 Firefox 200 NaN
4698 Chrome 200 NaN
4699 Safari 404 NaN
4700 IE10 404 NaN
4701 Konqueror 301 NaN
4702  
4703 Or we can use "axis-style" keyword arguments
4704  
4705 >>> df.reindex(['http_status', 'user_agent'], axis="columns")
4706 http_status user_agent
4707 Firefox 200 NaN
4708 Chrome 200 NaN
4709 Safari 404 NaN
4710 IE10 404 NaN
4711 Konqueror 301 NaN
4712  
4713 To further illustrate the filling functionality in
4714 ``reindex``, we will create a dataframe with a
4715 monotonically increasing index (for example, a sequence
4716 of dates).
4717  
4718 >>> date_index = pd.date_range('1/1/2010', periods=6, freq='D')
4719 >>> df2 = pd.DataFrame({{"prices": [100, 101, np.nan, 100, 89, 88]}},
4720 ... index=date_index)
4721 >>> df2
4722 prices
4723 2010-01-01 100.0
4724 2010-01-02 101.0
4725 2010-01-03 NaN
4726 2010-01-04 100.0
4727 2010-01-05 89.0
4728 2010-01-06 88.0
4729  
4730 Suppose we decide to expand the dataframe to cover a wider
4731 date range.
4732  
4733 >>> date_index2 = pd.date_range('12/29/2009', periods=10, freq='D')
4734 >>> df2.reindex(date_index2)
4735 prices
4736 2009-12-29 NaN
4737 2009-12-30 NaN
4738 2009-12-31 NaN
4739 2010-01-01 100.0
4740 2010-01-02 101.0
4741 2010-01-03 NaN
4742 2010-01-04 100.0
4743 2010-01-05 89.0
4744 2010-01-06 88.0
4745 2010-01-07 NaN
4746  
4747 The index entries that did not have a value in the original data frame
4748 (for example, '2009-12-29') are by default filled with ``NaN``.
4749 If desired, we can fill in the missing values using one of several
4750 options.
4751  
4752 For example, to back-propagate the last valid value to fill the ``NaN``
4753 values, pass ``bfill`` as an argument to the ``method`` keyword.
4754  
4755 >>> df2.reindex(date_index2, method='bfill')
4756 prices
4757 2009-12-29 100.0
4758 2009-12-30 100.0
4759 2009-12-31 100.0
4760 2010-01-01 100.0
4761 2010-01-02 101.0
4762 2010-01-03 NaN
4763 2010-01-04 100.0
4764 2010-01-05 89.0
4765 2010-01-06 88.0
4766 2010-01-07 NaN
4767  
4768 Please note that the ``NaN`` value present in the original dataframe
4769 (at index value 2010-01-03) will not be filled by any of the
4770 value propagation schemes. This is because filling while reindexing
4771 does not look at dataframe values, but only compares the original and

4774  
4775 See the :ref:`user guide <basics.reindexing>` for more.

4860 @final
4861 def _reindex_with_indexers(
4862 self: FrameOrSeries,
4863 reindexers,
4864 fill_value=None,
4865 copy: bool_t = False,
4866 allow_dups: bool_t = False,
4867 ) -> FrameOrSeries:
4868 """allow_dups indicates an internal call here"""
4869 # reindex doing multiple operations on different axes if indicated
4870 new_data = self._mgr
4871 for axis in sorted(reindexers.keys()):
4872 index, indexer = reindexers[axis]
4873 baxis = self._get_block_manager_axis(axis)
4874  
4875 if index is None:
4876 continue
4877  
4878 index = ensure_index(index)
4879 if indexer is not None:
4880 indexer = ensure_platform_int(indexer)
4881  
4882 # TODO: speed up on homogeneous DataFrame objects
4883 new_data = new_data.reindex_indexer(
4884 index,
4885 indexer,
4886 axis=baxis,
4887 fill_value=fill_value,
4888 allow_dups=allow_dups,
4889 copy=copy,
4890 )
4891 # If we've made a copy once, no need to make another one
4892 copy = False
4893  
4894 if copy and new_data is self._mgr:
4895 new_data = new_data.copy()

4921 The axis to filter on, expressed either as an index (int)

4924

4927 same type as input object

4932 by label(s) or a boolean array.

4937 enforced to be mutually exclusive.
4938

4956 rabbit 4 6
4957  
4958 >>> # select columns by regular expression
4959 >>> df.filter(regex='e$', axis=1)
4960 one three
4961 mouse 1 3
4962 rabbit 4 6
4963  
4964 >>> # select rows containing 'bbi'
4965 >>> df.filter(like='bbi', axis=0)
4966 one two three
4967 rabbit 4 5 6

4970 if nkw > 1:
4971 raise TypeError(
4972 "Keyword arguments `items`, `like`, or `regex` "
4973 "are mutually exclusive"
4974 )
4975  
4976 if axis is None:
4977 axis = self._info_axis_name
4978 labels = self._get_axis(axis)
4979  
4980 if items is not None:
4981 name = self._get_axis_name(axis)
4982 return self.reindex(**{name: [r for r in items if r in labels]})
4983 elif like:

4986 assert like is not None # needed for mypy
4987 return like in ensure_str(x)
4988  
4989 values = labels.map(f)
4990 return self.loc(axis=axis)[values]
4991 elif regex:
4992

4994 return matcher.search(ensure_str(x)) is not None
4995  
4996 matcher = re.compile(regex)
4997 values = labels.map(f)
4998 return self.loc(axis=axis)[values]
4999 else:
5000 raise TypeError("Must pass either `items`, `like`, or `regex`")

5405 :class:`~pandas.Series`.

5407 Notes
5408 -----
5409 Use ``.pipe`` when chaining together functions that expect
5410 Series, DataFrames or GroupBy objects. Instead of writing
5411

5413

5417 ... .pipe(g, arg1=a)

5419 ... ) # doctest: +SKIP
5420  
5421 If you have a function that takes the data as (say) the second
5422 argument, pass a tuple indicating which keyword expects the
5423 data. For example, suppose ``f`` takes its data as ``arg2``:
5424  
5425 >>> (df.pipe(h)
5426 ... .pipe(g, arg1=a)
5427 ... .pipe((func, 'arg2'), arg1=a, arg3=c)
5428 ... ) # doctest: +SKIP

5827 @final
5828 def copy(self: FrameOrSeries, deep: bool_t = True) -> FrameOrSeries:
5829 """
5830 Make a copy of this object's indices and data.
5831  
5832 When ``deep=True`` (default), a new object will be created with a
5833 copy of the calling object's data and indices. Modifications to
5834 the data or indices of the copy will not be reflected in the
5835 original object (see notes below).
5836  
5837 When ``deep=False``, a new object will be created without copying
5838 the calling object's data or index (only references to the data
5839 and index are copied). Any changes to the data of the original
5840 will be reflected in the shallow copy (and vice versa).
5841  
5842 Parameters
5843 ----------
5844 deep : bool, default True
5845 Make a deep copy, including a copy of the data and the indices.
5846 With ``deep=False`` neither the indices nor the data are copied.
5847  
5848 Returns
5849 -------
5850 copy : Series or DataFrame
5851 Object type matches caller.
5852  
5853 Notes
5854 -----
5855 When ``deep=True``, data is copied but actual Python objects
5856 will not be copied recursively, only the reference to the object.
5857 This is in contrast to `copy.deepcopy` in the Standard Library,
5858 which recursively copies object data (see examples below).
5859  
5860 While ``Index`` objects are copied when ``deep=True``, the underlying
5861 numpy array is not copied for performance reasons. Since ``Index`` is
5862 immutable, the underlying data can be safely shared and a copy
5863 is not needed.
5864  
5865 Examples
5866 --------
5867 >>> s = pd.Series([1, 2], index=["a", "b"])
5868 >>> s
5869 a 1
5870 b 2
5871 dtype: int64
5872  
5873 >>> s_copy = s.copy()
5874 >>> s_copy
5875 a 1
5876 b 2
5877 dtype: int64
5878  
5879 **Shallow copy versus default (deep) copy:**
5880  
5881 >>> s = pd.Series([1, 2], index=["a", "b"])
5882 >>> deep = s.copy()
5883 >>> shallow = s.copy(deep=False)
5884  
5885 Shallow copy shares data and index with original.
5886  
5887 >>> s is shallow
5888 False
5889 >>> s.values is shallow.values and s.index is shallow.index
5890 True
5891  
5892 Deep copy has own copy of data and index.
5893  
5894 >>> s is deep
5895 False
5896 >>> s.values is deep.values or s.index is deep.index
5897 False
5898  
5899 Updates to the data shared by shallow copy and original is reflected
5900 in both; deep copy remains unchanged.
5901  
5902 >>> s[0] = 3
5903 >>> shallow[1] = 4
5904 >>> s
5905 a 3
5906 b 4
5907 dtype: int64
5908 >>> shallow
5909 a 3
5910 b 4
5911 dtype: int64
5912 >>> deep
5913 a 1
5914 b 2
5915 dtype: int64
5916  
5917 Note that when copying an object containing Python objects, a deep copy
5918 will copy the data, but will not do so recursively. Updating a nested
5919 data object will be reflected in the deep copy.
5920  
5921 >>> s = pd.Series([[1, 2], [3, 4]])
5922 >>> deep = s.copy()
5923 >>> s[0][0] = 10
5924 >>> s
5925 0 [10, 2]
5926 1 [3, 4]
5927 dtype: object
5928 >>> deep
5929 0 [10, 2]
5930 1 [3, 4]
5931 dtype: object
5932 """
5933 data = self._mgr.copy(deep=deep)
5934 self._clear_item_cache()
5935 return self._constructor(data).__finalize__(self, method="copy")
5936  
5937 @final
5938 def __copy__(self: FrameOrSeries, deep: bool_t = True) -> FrameOrSeries:
5939 return self.copy(deep=deep)

6623 def interpolate(
6624 self: FrameOrSeries,
6625 method: str = "linear",
6626 axis: Axis = 0,
6627 limit: int | None = None,
6628 inplace: bool_t = False,
6629 limit_direction: str | None = None,
6630 limit_area: str | None = None,
6631 downcast: str | None = None,
6632 **kwargs,
6633 ) -> FrameOrSeries | None:
6634 """
6635 Fill NaN values using an interpolation method.
6636  
6637 Please note that only ``method='linear'`` is supported for
6638 DataFrame/Series with a MultiIndex.
6639  
6640 Parameters
6641 ----------
6642 method : str, default 'linear'
6643 Interpolation technique to use. One of:
6644  
6645 * 'linear': Ignore the index and treat the values as equally
6646 spaced. This is the only method supported on MultiIndexes.
6647 * 'time': Works on daily and higher resolution data to interpolate
6648 given length of interval.
6649 * 'index', 'values': use the actual numerical values of the index.
6650 * 'pad': Fill in NaNs using existing values.
6651 * 'nearest', 'zero', 'slinear', 'quadratic', 'cubic', 'spline',
6652 'barycentric', 'polynomial': Passed to
6653 `scipy.interpolate.interp1d`. These methods use the numerical
6654 values of the index. Both 'polynomial' and 'spline' require that
6655 you also specify an `order` (int), e.g.
6656 ``df.interpolate(method='polynomial', order=5)``.
6657 * 'krogh', 'piecewise_polynomial', 'spline', 'pchip', 'akima',
6658 'cubicspline': Wrappers around the SciPy interpolation methods of
6659 similar names. See `Notes`.
6660 * 'from_derivatives': Refers to
6661 `scipy.interpolate.BPoly.from_derivatives` which
6662 replaces 'piecewise_polynomial' interpolation method in
6663 scipy 0.18.
6664  
6665 axis : {{0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns', None}}, default None
6666 Axis to interpolate along.
6667 limit : int, optional
6668 Maximum number of consecutive NaNs to fill. Must be greater than
6669 0.
6670 inplace : bool, default False
6671 Update the data in place if possible.
6672 limit_direction : {{'forward', 'backward', 'both'}}, Optional
6673 Consecutive NaNs will be filled in this direction.
6674  
6675 If limit is specified:
  • E501 Line too long (87 > 79 characters)
6676 * If 'method' is 'pad' or 'ffill', 'limit_direction' must be 'forward'.
  • E501 Line too long (81 > 79 characters)
6677 * If 'method' is 'backfill' or 'bfill', 'limit_direction' must be
6678 'backwards'.
6679  
6680 If 'limit' is not specified:
  • E501 Line too long (81 > 79 characters)
6681 * If 'method' is 'backfill' or 'bfill', the default is 'backward'
6682 * else the default is 'forward'
6683  
6684 .. versionchanged:: 1.1.0
  • E501 Line too long (81 > 79 characters)
6685 raises ValueError if `limit_direction` is 'forward' or 'both' and
6686 method is 'backfill' or 'bfill'.
  • E501 Line too long (82 > 79 characters)
6687 raises ValueError if `limit_direction` is 'backward' or 'both' and
6688 method is 'pad' or 'ffill'.
6689  
6690 limit_area : {{`None`, 'inside', 'outside'}}, default None
6691 If limit is specified, consecutive NaNs will be filled with this
6692 restriction.
6693  
6694 * ``None``: No fill restriction.
6695 * 'inside': Only fill NaNs surrounded by valid values
6696 (interpolate).
6697 * 'outside': Only fill NaNs outside valid values (extrapolate).
6698  
6699 downcast : optional, 'infer' or None, defaults to None
6700 Downcast dtypes if possible.
6701 ``**kwargs`` : optional
6702 Keyword arguments to pass on to the interpolating function.
6703  
6704 Returns
6705 -------
6706 Series or DataFrame or None
6707 Returns the same object type as the caller, interpolated at
6708 some or all ``NaN`` values or None if ``inplace=True``.
6709  
6710 See Also
6711 --------
6712 fillna : Fill missing values using different methods.
6713 scipy.interpolate.Akima1DInterpolator : Piecewise cubic polynomials
6714 (Akima interpolator).
6715 scipy.interpolate.BPoly.from_derivatives : Piecewise polynomial in the
6716 Bernstein basis.
6717 scipy.interpolate.interp1d : Interpolate a 1-D function.
6718 scipy.interpolate.KroghInterpolator : Interpolate polynomial (Krogh
6719 interpolator).
6720 scipy.interpolate.PchipInterpolator : PCHIP 1-d monotonic cubic
6721 interpolation.
6722 scipy.interpolate.CubicSpline : Cubic spline data interpolator.
6723  
6724 Notes
6725 -----
6726 The 'krogh', 'piecewise_polynomial', 'spline', 'pchip' and 'akima'
6727 methods are wrappers around the respective SciPy implementations of
6728 similar names. These use the actual numerical values of the index.
6729 For more information on their behavior, see the
6730 `SciPy documentation
6731 <https://docs.scipy.org/doc/scipy/reference/interpolate.html#univariate-interpolation>`__
6732 and `SciPy tutorial
6733 <https://docs.scipy.org/doc/scipy/reference/tutorial/interpolate.html>`__.
6734  
6735 Examples
6736 --------
6737 Filling in ``NaN`` in a :class:`~pandas.Series` via linear
6738 interpolation.
6739  
6740 >>> s = pd.Series([0, 1, np.nan, 3])
6741 >>> s

6801 is no entry before it to use for interpolation.

6922 @final
6923 def asof(self, where, subset=None):
6924 """
6925 Return the last row(s) without any NaNs before `where`.
6926  
6927 The last row (for each element in `where`, if list) without any
6928 NaN is taken.
6929 In case of a :class:`~pandas.DataFrame`, the last row without NaN
6930 considering only the subset of columns (if not `None`)
6931  
6932 If there is no good value, NaN is returned for a Series or
6933 a Series of NaN values for a DataFrame
6934  
6935 Parameters
6936 ----------
6937 where : date or array-like of dates
6938 Date(s) before which the last row(s) are returned.
6939 subset : str or array-like of str, default `None`
6940 For DataFrame, if not `None`, only use these columns to
6941 check for NaNs.
6942  
6943 Returns
6944 -------
6945 scalar, Series, or DataFrame
6946  
6947 The return can be:
6948  
6949 * scalar : when `self` is a Series and `where` is a scalar
6950 * Series: when `self` is a Series and `where` is an array-like,
6951 or when `self` is a DataFrame and `where` is a scalar
6952 * DataFrame : when `self` is a DataFrame and `where` is an
6953 array-like
6954  
6955 Return scalar, Series, or DataFrame.
6956  
6957 See Also
6958 --------
6959 merge_asof : Perform an asof merge. Similar to left join.
6960  
6961 Notes
6962 -----
6963 Dates are assumed to be sorted. Raises if this is not the case.
6964  
6965 Examples
6966 --------
6967 A Series and a scalar `where`.
6968  
6969 >>> s = pd.Series([1, 2, np.nan, 4], index=[10, 20, 30, 40])
6970 >>> s
6971 10 1.0
6972 20 2.0
6973 30 NaN
6974 40 4.0
6975 dtype: float64
6976  
6977 >>> s.asof(20)
6978 2.0
6979  
6980 For a sequence `where`, a Series is returned. The first value is
6981 NaN, because the first element of `where` is before the first
6982 index value.
6983  
6984 >>> s.asof([5, 20])
6985 5 NaN
6986 20 2.0
6987 dtype: float64
6988  
6989 Missing values are not considered. The following is ``2.0``, not
6990 NaN, even though NaN is at the index location for ``30``.
6991  
6992 >>> s.asof(30)
6993 2.0
6994  
6995 Take all columns into consideration
6996  
6997 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'a': [10, 20, 30, 40, 50],
6998 ... 'b': [None, None, None, None, 500]},
6999 ... index=pd.DatetimeIndex(['2018-02-27 09:01:00',
7000 ... '2018-02-27 09:02:00',
7001 ... '2018-02-27 09:03:00',
7002 ... '2018-02-27 09:04:00',
7003 ... '2018-02-27 09:05:00']))
7004 >>> df.asof(pd.DatetimeIndex(['2018-02-27 09:03:30',
7005 ... '2018-02-27 09:04:30']))
7006 a b
7007 2018-02-27 09:03:30 NaN NaN
7008 2018-02-27 09:04:30 NaN NaN
7009  
7010 Take a single column into consideration
7011  
7012 >>> df.asof(pd.DatetimeIndex(['2018-02-27 09:03:30',
7013 ... '2018-02-27 09:04:30']),
7014 ... subset=['a'])
7015 a b
7016 2018-02-27 09:03:30 30.0 NaN
7017 2018-02-27 09:04:30 40.0 NaN
7018 """
7019 if isinstance(where, str):
7020 where = Timestamp(where)
7021  
7022 if not self.index.is_monotonic:
7023 raise ValueError("asof requires a sorted index")
7024  
7025 is_series = isinstance(self, ABCSeries)
7026 if is_series:
7027 if subset is not None:
7028 raise ValueError("subset is not valid for Series")
7029 else:
7030 if subset is None:
7031 subset = self.columns
7032 if not is_list_like(subset):
7033 subset = [subset]
7034  
7035 is_list = is_list_like(where)
7036 if not is_list:
7037 start = self.index[0]
7038 if isinstance(self.index, PeriodIndex):
7039 where = Period(where, freq=self.index.freq)
7040  
7041 if where < start:
7042 if not is_series:
7043 return self._constructor_sliced(
7044 index=self.columns, name=where, dtype=np.float64
7045 )
7046 return np.nan
7047  
7048 # It's always much faster to use a *while* loop here for
7049 # Series than pre-computing all the NAs. However a
7050 # *while* loop is extremely expensive for DataFrame
7051 # so we later pre-compute all the NAs and use the same
7052 # code path whether *where* is a scalar or list.
7053 # See PR: https://github.com/pandas-dev/pandas/pull/14476
7054 if is_series:
7055 loc = self.index.searchsorted(where, side="right")
7056 if loc > 0:
7057 loc -= 1
7058  
7059 values = self._values
7060 while loc > 0 and isna(values[loc]):
7061 loc -= 1
7062 return values[loc]
7063  
7064 if not isinstance(where, Index):
7065 where = Index(where) if is_list else Index([where])
7066  
7067 nulls = self.isna() if is_series else self[subset].isna().any(1)
7068 if nulls.all():
7069 if is_series:
7070 self = cast("Series", self)
7071 return self._constructor(np.nan, index=where, name=self.name)
7072 elif is_list:
7073 self = cast("DataFrame", self)
  • E501 Line too long (83 > 79 characters)
7074 return self._constructor(np.nan, index=where, columns=self.columns)
7075 else:
7076 self = cast("DataFrame", self)
7077 return self._constructor_sliced(
7078 np.nan, index=self.columns, name=where[0]
7079 )
7080  
7081 locs = self.index.asof_locs(where, ~(nulls._values))
7082  
7083 # mask the missing
7084 missing = locs == -1
7085 data = self.take(locs)
7086 data.index = where
7087 data.loc[missing] = np.nan
7088 return data if is_list else data.iloc[-1]

7093 @doc(klass=_shared_doc_kwargs["klass"])
7094 def isna(self: FrameOrSeries) -> FrameOrSeries:
7095 """
7096 Detect missing values.
7097  
7098 Return a boolean same-sized object indicating if the values are NA.
7099 NA values, such as None or :attr:`numpy.NaN`, gets mapped to True
7100 values.
7101 Everything else gets mapped to False values. Characters such as empty
7102 strings ``''`` or :attr:`numpy.inf` are not considered NA values
7103 (unless you set ``pandas.options.mode.use_inf_as_na = True``).
7104  
7105 Returns
7106 -------
7107 {klass}
7108 Mask of bool values for each element in {klass} that
7109 indicates whether an element is an NA value.
7110  
7111 See Also
7112 --------
7113 {klass}.isnull : Alias of isna.
7114 {klass}.notna : Boolean inverse of isna.
7115 {klass}.dropna : Omit axes labels with missing values.
7116 isna : Top-level isna.
7117  
7118 Examples
7119 --------
7120 Show which entries in a DataFrame are NA.
7121  
7122 >>> df = pd.DataFrame(dict(age=[5, 6, np.NaN],
7123 ... born=[pd.NaT, pd.Timestamp('1939-05-27'),
7124 ... pd.Timestamp('1940-04-25')],
7125 ... name=['Alfred', 'Batman', ''],
7126 ... toy=[None, 'Batmobile', 'Joker']))
7127 >>> df
7128 age born name toy
7129 0 5.0 NaT Alfred None
7130 1 6.0 1939-05-27 Batman Batmobile
7131 2 NaN 1940-04-25 Joker
7132  
7133 >>> df.isna()
7134 age born name toy
7135 0 False True False True
7136 1 False False False False
7137 2 True False False False
7138  
7139 Show which entries in a Series are NA.
7140  
7141 >>> ser = pd.Series([5, 6, np.NaN])
7142 >>> ser
7143 0 5.0
7144 1 6.0
7145 2 NaN
7146 dtype: float64
7147  
7148 >>> ser.isna()
7149 0 False
7150 1 False
7151 2 True
7152 dtype: bool
7153 """
7154 return isna(self).__finalize__(self, method="isna")
7155

7160 @doc(klass=_shared_doc_kwargs["klass"])
7161 def notna(self: FrameOrSeries) -> FrameOrSeries:
7162 """
7163 Detect existing (non-missing) values.
7164  
7165 Return a boolean same-sized object indicating if the values are not NA.
7166 Non-missing values get mapped to True. Characters such as empty
7167 strings ``''`` or :attr:`numpy.inf` are not considered NA values
7168 (unless you set ``pandas.options.mode.use_inf_as_na = True``).
7169 NA values, such as None or :attr:`numpy.NaN`, get mapped to False
7170 values.
7171  
7172 Returns
7173 -------
7174 {klass}
7175 Mask of bool values for each element in {klass} that
7176 indicates whether an element is not an NA value.

7711 @doc(**_shared_doc_kwargs)
7712 def resample(
7713 self,
7714 rule,
7715 axis=0,

7717 label: str | None = None,

7727 """
7728 Resample time-series data.
7729  
  • E501 Line too long (82 > 79 characters)
7730 Convenience method for frequency conversion and resampling of time series.
  • E501 Line too long (83 > 79 characters)
7731 The object must have a datetime-like index (`DatetimeIndex`, `PeriodIndex`,
  • E501 Line too long (82 > 79 characters)
7732 or `TimedeltaIndex`), or the caller must pass the label of a datetime-like
7733 series/index to the ``on``/``level`` keyword parameter.
7734  
7735 Parameters
7736 ----------
7737 rule : DateOffset, Timedelta or str
7738 The offset string or object representing target conversion.
7739 axis : {{0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}}, default 0
7740 Which axis to use for up- or down-sampling. For `Series` this
7741 will default to 0, i.e. along the rows. Must be
7742 `DatetimeIndex`, `TimedeltaIndex` or `PeriodIndex`.
7743 closed : {{'right', 'left'}}, default None
7744 Which side of bin interval is closed. The default is 'left'
7745 for all frequency offsets except for 'M', 'A', 'Q', 'BM',
7746 'BA', 'BQ', and 'W' which all have a default of 'right'.
7747 label : {{'right', 'left'}}, default None
7748 Which bin edge label to label bucket with. The default is 'left'
7749 for all frequency offsets except for 'M', 'A', 'Q', 'BM',
7750 'BA', 'BQ', and 'W' which all have a default of 'right'.
7751 convention : {{'start', 'end', 's', 'e'}}, default 'start'
7752 For `PeriodIndex` only, controls whether to use the start or
7753 end of `rule`.
7754 kind : {{'timestamp', 'period'}}, optional, default None
7755 Pass 'timestamp' to convert the resulting index to a
7756 `DateTimeIndex` or 'period' to convert it to a `PeriodIndex`.
7757 By default the input representation is retained.
7758 loffset : timedelta, default None
7759 Adjust the resampled time labels.
7760  
7761 .. deprecated:: 1.1.0
  • E501 Line too long (80 > 79 characters)
7762 You should add the loffset to the `df.index` after the resample.
7763 See below.
7764  
7765 base : int, default 0
7766 For frequencies that evenly subdivide 1 day, the "origin" of the
7767 aggregated intervals. For example, for '5min' frequency, base could
7768 range from 0 through 4. Defaults to 0.
7769  
7770 .. deprecated:: 1.1.0
7771 The new arguments that you should use are 'offset' or 'origin'.
7772  
7773 on : str, optional
7774 For a DataFrame, column to use instead of index for resampling.
7775 Column must be datetime-like.
7776 level : str or int, optional
7777 For a MultiIndex, level (name or number) to use for
7778 resampling. `level` must be datetime-like.
7779 origin : {{'epoch', 'start', 'start_day', 'end', 'end_day'}}, Timestamp
7780 or str, default 'start_day'
  • E501 Line too long (81 > 79 characters)
7781 The timestamp on which to adjust the grouping. The timezone of origin
7782 must match the timezone of the index.
7783 If a timestamp is not used, these values are also supported:
7784  
7785 - 'epoch': `origin` is 1970-01-01
7786 - 'start': `origin` is the first value of the timeseries
  • E501 Line too long (82 > 79 characters)
7787 - 'start_day': `origin` is the first day at midnight of the timeseries
7788  
7789 .. versionadded:: 1.1.0
7790  
7791 - 'end': `origin` is the last value of the timeseries
7792 - 'end_day': `origin` is the ceiling midnight of the last day

7840 Downsample the series into 3 minute bins and sum the values
7841 of the timestamps falling into a bin.
7842  
7843 >>> series.resample('3T').sum()
7844 2000-01-01 00:00:00 3
7845 2000-01-01 00:03:00 12
7846 2000-01-01 00:06:00 21
7847 Freq: 3T, dtype: int64
7848  
7849 Downsample the series into 3 minute bins as above, but label each
7850 bin using the right edge instead of the left. Please note that the
7851 value in the bucket used as the label is not included in the bucket,
7852 which it labels. For example, in the original series the
7853 bucket ``2000-01-01 00:03:00`` contains the value 3, but the summed
7854 value in the resampled bucket with the label ``2000-01-01 00:03:00``
7855 does not include 3 (if it did, the summed value would be 6, not 3).
7856 To include this value close the right side of the bin interval as
7857 illustrated in the example below this one.
7858  
7859 >>> series.resample('3T', label='right').sum()
7860 2000-01-01 00:03:00 3
7861 2000-01-01 00:06:00 12
7862 2000-01-01 00:09:00 21
7863 Freq: 3T, dtype: int64
7864

7866 side of the bin interval.

7871 2000-01-01 00:06:00 15
7872 2000-01-01 00:09:00 15

8280 @final
8281 def rank(
8282 self: FrameOrSeries,
8283 axis=0,
8284 method: str = "average",
8285 numeric_only: bool_t | None = None,
8286 na_option: str = "keep",
8287 ascending: bool_t = True,
8288 pct: bool_t = False,
8289 ) -> FrameOrSeries:
8290 """
8291 Compute numerical data ranks (1 through n) along axis.
8292  
8293 By default, equal values are assigned a rank that is the average of the
8294 ranks of those values.
8295  
8296 Parameters
8297 ----------
8298 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0
8299 Index to direct ranking.
8300 method : {'average', 'min', 'max', 'first', 'dense'}, default 'average'
  • E501 Line too long (82 > 79 characters)
8301 How to rank the group of records that have the same value (i.e. ties):
8302  
8303 * average: average rank of the group
8304 * min: lowest rank in the group
8305 * max: highest rank in the group
8306 * first: ranks assigned in order they appear in the array
8307 * dense: like 'min', but rank always increases by 1 between groups.
8308  
8309 numeric_only : bool, optional
8310 For DataFrame objects, rank only numeric columns if set to True.
8311 na_option : {'keep', 'top', 'bottom'}, default 'keep'
8312 How to rank NaN values:
8313  
8314 * keep: assign NaN rank to NaN values
8315 * top: assign lowest rank to NaN values
8316 * bottom: assign highest rank to NaN values
8317  
8318 ascending : bool, default True
8319 Whether or not the elements should be ranked in ascending order.
8320 pct : bool, default False
8321 Whether or not to display the returned rankings in percentile
8322 form.
8323  
8324 Returns
8325 -------
8326 same type as caller
8327 Return a Series or DataFrame with data ranks as values.
8328  
8329 See Also
8330 --------
8331 core.groupby.GroupBy.rank : Rank of values within each group.
8332  
8333 Examples
8334 --------
8335 >>> df = pd.DataFrame(data={'Animal': ['cat', 'penguin', 'dog',
8336 ... 'spider', 'snake'],
8337 ... 'Number_legs': [4, 2, 4, 8, np.nan]})
8338 >>> df
8339 Animal Number_legs
8340 0 cat 4.0
8341 1 penguin 2.0
8342 2 dog 4.0
8343 3 spider 8.0
8344 4 snake NaN
8345  
8346 The following example shows how the method behaves with the above
8347 parameters:
8348  
8349 * default_rank: this is the default behaviour obtained without using
8350 any parameter.
8351 * max_rank: setting ``method = 'max'`` the records that have the
8352 same values are ranked using the highest rank (e.g.: since 'cat'
8353 and 'dog' are both in the 2nd and 3rd position, rank 3 is assigned.)
8354 * NA_bottom: choosing ``na_option = 'bottom'``, if there are records
8355 with NaN values they are placed at the bottom of the ranking.
8356 * pct_rank: when setting ``pct = True``, the ranking is expressed as
8357 percentile rank.
8358  
8359 >>> df['default_rank'] = df['Number_legs'].rank()
8360 >>> df['max_rank'] = df['Number_legs'].rank(method='max')
8361 >>> df['NA_bottom'] = df['Number_legs'].rank(na_option='bottom')
8362 >>> df['pct_rank'] = df['Number_legs'].rank(pct=True)
8363 >>> df
8364 Animal Number_legs default_rank max_rank NA_bottom pct_rank
8365 0 cat 4.0 2.5 3.0 2.5 0.625
8366 1 penguin 2.0 1.0 1.0 1.0 0.250
8367 2 dog 4.0 2.5 3.0 2.5 0.625

8899 """
8900 Replace values where the condition is {cond_rev}.
8901  
8902 Parameters
8903 ----------
8904 cond : bool {klass}, array-like, or callable
8905 Where `cond` is {cond}, keep the original value. Where
8906 {cond_rev}, replace with corresponding value from `other`.
8907 If `cond` is callable, it is computed on the {klass} and
8908 should return boolean {klass} or array. The callable must
8909 not change input {klass} (though pandas doesn't check it).
8910 other : scalar, {klass}, or callable
8911 Entries where `cond` is {cond_rev} are replaced with
8912 corresponding value from `other`.
8913 If other is callable, it is computed on the {klass} and
8914 should return scalar or {klass}. The callable must not
8915 change input {klass} (though pandas doesn't check it).
8916 inplace : bool, default False
8917 Whether to perform the operation in place on the data.
8918 axis : int, default None
8919 Alignment axis if needed.
8920 level : int, default None
8921 Alignment level if needed.
8922 errors : str, {{'raise', 'ignore'}}, default 'raise'
8923 Note that currently this parameter won't affect
8924 the results and will always coerce to a suitable dtype.
8925  
8926 - 'raise' : allow exceptions to be raised.
8927 - 'ignore' : suppress exceptions. On error return original object.
8928  
8929 try_cast : bool, default None
8930 Try to cast the result back to the input type (if possible).
8931  
8932 .. deprecated:: 1.3.0
8933 Manually cast back if necessary.
8934  
8935 Returns
8936 -------
8937 Same type as caller or None if ``inplace=True``.
8938  
8939 See Also
8940 --------
8941 :func:`DataFrame.{name_other}` : Return an object of same shape as
8942 self.
8943  
8944 Notes
8945 -----
8946 The {name} method is an application of the if-then idiom. For each
8947 element in the calling DataFrame, if ``cond`` is ``{cond}`` the
8948 element is used; otherwise the corresponding element from the DataFrame
8949 ``other`` is used.
8950  
8951 The signature for :func:`DataFrame.where` differs from
8952 :func:`numpy.where`. Roughly ``df1.where(m, df2)`` is equivalent to
8953 ``np.where(m, df1, df2)``.
8954  
8955 For further details and examples see the ``{name}`` documentation in
8956 :ref:`indexing <indexing.where_mask>`.
8957  
8958 Examples
8959 --------
8960 >>> s = pd.Series(range(5))

8962 0 NaN
8963 1 1.0
8964 2 2.0
8965 3 3.0
8966 4 4.0
8967 dtype: float64
8968 >>> s.mask(s > 0)
8969 0 0.0
8970 1 NaN
8971 2 NaN
8972 3 NaN
8973 4 NaN
8974 dtype: float64
8975  
8976 >>> s.where(s > 1, 10)
8977 0 10
8978 1 10
8979 2 2
8980 3 3
8981 4 4
8982 dtype: int64
8983 >>> s.mask(s > 1, 10)
8984 0 0
8985 1 1
8986 2 10
8987 3 10
8988 4 10
8989 dtype: int64
8990  
8991 >>> df = pd.DataFrame(np.arange(10).reshape(-1, 2), columns=['A', 'B'])
8992 >>> df
8993 A B
8994 0 0 1
8995 1 2 3
8996 2 4 5
8997 3 6 7
8998 4 8 9
8999 >>> m = df % 3 == 0
9000 >>> df.where(m, -df)
9001 A B
9002 0 0 -1
9003 1 -2 3
9004 2 -4 -5

9079 def shift(
9080 self: FrameOrSeries, periods=1, freq=None, axis=0, fill_value=None
9081 ) -> FrameOrSeries:
9082 """
9083 Shift index by desired number of periods with an optional time `freq`.
9084  
9085 When `freq` is not passed, shift the index without realigning the data.
9086 If `freq` is passed (in this case, the index must be date or datetime,
9087 or it will raise a `NotImplementedError`), the index will be
9088 increased using the periods and the `freq`. `freq` can be inferred
9089 when specified as "infer" as long as either freq or inferred_freq
9090 attribute is set in the index.
9091  
9092 Parameters
9093 ----------
9094 periods : int
9095 Number of periods to shift. Can be positive or negative.
9096 freq : DateOffset, tseries.offsets, timedelta, or str, optional
9097 Offset to use from the tseries module or time rule (e.g. 'EOM').
9098 If `freq` is specified then the index values are shifted but the
9099 data is not realigned. That is, use `freq` if you would like to
9100 extend the index when shifting and preserve the original data.
9101 If `freq` is specified as "infer" then it will be inferred from
9102 the freq or inferred_freq attributes of the index. If neither of
9103 those attributes exist, a ValueError is thrown.
9104 axis : {{0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns', None}}, default None
9105 Shift direction.
9106 fill_value : object, optional
9107 The scalar value to use for newly introduced missing values.
9108 the default depends on the dtype of `self`.
9109 For numeric data, ``np.nan`` is used.
9110 For datetime, timedelta, or period data, etc. :attr:`NaT` is used.
9111 For extension dtypes, ``self.dtype.na_value`` is used.
9112  
9113 .. versionchanged:: 1.1.0

9116 -------
9117 {klass}
9118 Copy of input object, shifted.

9122 Index.shift : Shift values of Index.
9123 DatetimeIndex.shift : Shift values of DatetimeIndex.
9124 PeriodIndex.shift : Shift values of PeriodIndex.
9125 tshift : Shift the time index, using the index's frequency if
9126 available.
9127

9532 def tz_localize(
9533 self: FrameOrSeries,
9534 tz,
9535 axis=0,
9536 level=None,
9537 copy: bool_t = True,
9538 ambiguous="raise",

9541 """
9542 Localize tz-naive index of a Series or DataFrame to target time zone.
9543  
9544 This operation localizes the Index. To localize the values in a
9545 timezone-naive Series, use :meth:`Series.dt.tz_localize`.
9546  
9547 Parameters
9548 ----------
9549 tz : str or tzinfo
9550 axis : the axis to localize
9551 level : int, str, default None
9552 If axis ia a MultiIndex, localize a specific level. Otherwise
9553 must be None.
9554 copy : bool, default True
9555 Also make a copy of the underlying data.
9556 ambiguous : 'infer', bool-ndarray, 'NaT', default 'raise'
9557 When clocks moved backward due to DST, ambiguous times may arise.
9558 For example in Central European Time (UTC+01), when going from
9559 03:00 DST to 02:00 non-DST, 02:30:00 local time occurs both at
9560 00:30:00 UTC and at 01:30:00 UTC. In such a situation, the
9561 `ambiguous` parameter dictates how ambiguous times should be
9562 handled.
9563  
9564 - 'infer' will attempt to infer fall dst-transition hours based on
9565 order
9566 - bool-ndarray where True signifies a DST time, False designates
9567 a non-DST time (note that this flag is only applicable for
9568 ambiguous times)
9569 - 'NaT' will return NaT where there are ambiguous times
9570 - 'raise' will raise an AmbiguousTimeError if there are ambiguous
9571 times.
9572 nonexistent : str, default 'raise'
9573 A nonexistent time does not exist in a particular timezone
9574 where clocks moved forward due to DST. Valid values are:
9575  
9576 - 'shift_forward' will shift the nonexistent time forward to the
9577 closest existing time
9578 - 'shift_backward' will shift the nonexistent time backward to the
9579 closest existing time
9580 - 'NaT' will return NaT where there are nonexistent times
9581 - timedelta objects will shift nonexistent times by the timedelta
9582 - 'raise' will raise an NonExistentTimeError if there are
9583 nonexistent times.
9584  
9585 Returns
9586 -------
9587 Series or DataFrame
9588 Same type as the input.
9589  
9590 Raises
9591 ------
9592 TypeError
9593 If the TimeSeries is tz-aware and tz is not None.
9594  
9595 Examples
9596 --------
9597 Localize local times:
9598  
9599 >>> s = pd.Series([1],
9600 ... index=pd.DatetimeIndex(['2018-09-15 01:30:00']))
9601 >>> s.tz_localize('CET')
9602 2018-09-15 01:30:00+02:00 1
9603 dtype: int64
9604  
9605 Be careful with DST changes. When there is sequential data, pandas
9606 can infer the DST time:
9607  
9608 >>> s = pd.Series(range(7),
9609 ... index=pd.DatetimeIndex(['2018-10-28 01:30:00',
9610 ... '2018-10-28 02:00:00',
9611 ... '2018-10-28 02:30:00',
9612 ... '2018-10-28 02:00:00',
9613 ... '2018-10-28 02:30:00',
9614 ... '2018-10-28 03:00:00',
9615 ... '2018-10-28 03:30:00']))
9616 >>> s.tz_localize('CET', ambiguous='infer')
9617 2018-10-28 01:30:00+02:00 0
9618 2018-10-28 02:00:00+02:00 1
9619 2018-10-28 02:30:00+02:00 2
9620 2018-10-28 02:00:00+01:00 3
9621 2018-10-28 02:30:00+01:00 4
9622 2018-10-28 03:00:00+01:00 5
9623 2018-10-28 03:30:00+01:00 6
9624 dtype: int64
9625

9643 >>> s = pd.Series(range(2),
