9783 """
9784 Generate descriptive statistics.
9785  
9786 Descriptive statistics include those that summarize the central
9787 tendency, dispersion and shape of a
9788 dataset's distribution, excluding ``NaN`` values.
9789  
9790 Analyzes both numeric and object series, as well
9791 as ``DataFrame`` column sets of mixed data types. The output
9792 will vary depending on what is provided. Refer to the notes
9793 below for more detail.
9794  
9795 Parameters
9796 ----------
9797 percentiles : list-like of numbers, optional
9798 The percentiles to include in the output. All should
9799 fall between 0 and 1. The default is
9800 ``[.25, .5, .75]``, which returns the 25th, 50th, and
9801 75th percentiles.
9802 include : 'all', list-like of dtypes or None (default), optional
9803 A white list of data types to include in the result. Ignored
9804 for ``Series``. Here are the options:
9805  
9806 - 'all' : All columns of the input will be included in the output.
9807 - A list-like of dtypes : Limits the results to the
9808 provided data types.
9809 To limit the result to numeric types submit
9810 ``numpy.number``. To limit it instead to object columns submit
9811 the ``numpy.object`` data type. Strings
9812 can also be used in the style of
9813 ``select_dtypes`` (e.g. ``df.describe(include=['O'])``). To
9814 select pandas categorical columns, use ``'category'``
9815 - None (default) : The result will include all numeric columns.
9816 exclude : list-like of dtypes or None (default), optional,
9817 A black list of data types to omit from the result. Ignored
9818 for ``Series``. Here are the options:
9819  
9820 - A list-like of dtypes : Excludes the provided data types
9821 from the result. To exclude numeric types submit
9822 ``numpy.number``. To exclude object columns submit the data
9823 type ``numpy.object``. Strings can also be used in the style of
9824 ``select_dtypes`` (e.g. ``df.describe(include=['O'])``). To
9825 exclude pandas categorical columns, use ``'category'``
9826 - None (default) : The result will exclude nothing.
9827 datetime_is_numeric : bool, default False
  • E501 Line too long (80 > 79 characters)
9828 Whether to treat datetime dtypes as numeric. This affects statistics
9829 calculated for the column. For DataFrame input, this also
9830 controls whether datetime columns are included by default.
9831  
9832 .. versionadded:: 1.1.0
9833  
9834 Returns
9835 -------
9836 Series or DataFrame
9837 Summary statistics of the Series or Dataframe provided.
9838  
9839 See Also
9840 --------
9841 DataFrame.count: Count number of non-NA/null observations.
9842 DataFrame.max: Maximum of the values in the object.
9843 DataFrame.min: Minimum of the values in the object.
9844 DataFrame.mean: Mean of the values.
9845 DataFrame.std: Standard deviation of the observations.
9846 DataFrame.select_dtypes: Subset of a DataFrame including/excluding
9847 columns based on their dtype.
9848  
9849 Notes
9850 -----
9851 For numeric data, the result's index will include ``count``,
9852 ``mean``, ``std``, ``min``, ``max`` as well as lower, ``50`` and
9853 upper percentiles. By default the lower percentile is ``25`` and the
9854 upper percentile is ``75``. The ``50`` percentile is the
9855 same as the median.
9856  
9857 For object data (e.g. strings or timestamps), the result's index
9858 will include ``count``, ``unique``, ``top``, and ``freq``. The ``top``
9859 is the most common value. The ``freq`` is the most common value's
9860 frequency. Timestamps also include the ``first`` and ``last`` items.
9861  
9862 If multiple object values have the highest count, then the
9863 ``count`` and ``top`` results will be arbitrarily chosen from
9864 among those with the highest count.
9865  
9866 For mixed data types provided via a ``DataFrame``, the default is to
9867 return only an analysis of numeric columns. If the dataframe consists
9868 only of object and categorical data without any numeric columns, the
9869 default is to return an analysis of both the object and categorical
9870 columns. If ``include='all'`` is provided as an option, the result
9871 will include a union of attributes of each type.
9872  
9873 The `include` and `exclude` parameters can be used to limit
9874 which columns in a ``DataFrame`` are analyzed for the output.
9875 The parameters are ignored when analyzing a ``Series``.
9876

10032 @final
10033 def pct_change(
10034 self: FrameOrSeries,
10035 periods=1,
10036 fill_method="pad",
10037 limit=None,
10038 freq=None,
10039 **kwargs,
10040 ) -> FrameOrSeries:
10041 """
10042 Percentage change between the current and a prior element.
10043  
10044 Computes the percentage change from the immediately previous row by
10045 default. This is useful in comparing the percentage of change in a time
10046 series of elements.
10047  
10048 Parameters
10049 ----------
10050 periods : int, default 1
10051 Periods to shift for forming percent change.
10052 fill_method : str, default 'pad'
10053 How to handle NAs before computing percent changes.
10054 limit : int, default None
10055 The number of consecutive NAs to fill before stopping.
10056 freq : DateOffset, timedelta, or str, optional
10057 Increment to use from time series API (e.g. 'M' or BDay()).
10058 **kwargs
10059 Additional keyword arguments are passed into
10060 `DataFrame.shift` or `Series.shift`.
10061  
10062 Returns
10063 -------
10064 chg : Series or DataFrame
10065 The same type as the calling object.
10066  
10067 See Also
10068 --------
10069 Series.diff : Compute the difference of two elements in a Series.
10070 DataFrame.diff : Compute the difference of two elements in a DataFrame.
10071 Series.shift : Shift the index by some number of periods.
10072 DataFrame.shift : Shift the index by some number of periods.
10073  
10074 Examples
10075 --------
10076 **Series**
10077  
10078 >>> s = pd.Series([90, 91, 85])
10079 >>> s
10080 0 90
10081 1 91
10082 2 85
10083 dtype: int64
10084  
10085 >>> s.pct_change()
10086 0 NaN
10087 1 0.011111
10088 2 -0.065934
10089 dtype: float64
10090  
10091 >>> s.pct_change(periods=2)
10092 0 NaN
10093 1 NaN
10094 2 -0.055556
10095 dtype: float64
10096  
10097 See the percentage change in a Series where filling NAs with last
10098 valid observation forward to next valid.
10099  
10100 >>> s = pd.Series([90, 91, None, 85])
10101 >>> s
10102 0 90.0
10103 1 91.0
10104 2 NaN
10105 3 85.0
10106 dtype: float64
10107  
10108 >>> s.pct_change(fill_method='ffill')
10109 0 NaN
10110 1 0.011111
10111 2 0.000000
10112 3 -0.065934
10113 dtype: float64
10114  
10115 **DataFrame**
10116  
10117 Percentage change in French franc, Deutsche Mark, and Italian lira from
10118 1980-01-01 to 1980-03-01.
10119  
10120 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({
10121 ... 'FR': [4.0405, 4.0963, 4.3149],
10122 ... 'GR': [1.7246, 1.7482, 1.8519],
10123 ... 'IT': [804.74, 810.01, 860.13]},
10124 ... index=['1980-01-01', '1980-02-01', '1980-03-01'])
10125 >>> df
10126 FR GR IT
10127 1980-01-01 4.0405 1.7246 804.74
10128 1980-02-01 4.0963 1.7482 810.01
10129 1980-03-01 4.3149 1.8519 860.13
10130  
10131 >>> df.pct_change()
10132 FR GR IT
10133 1980-01-01 NaN NaN NaN
10134 1980-02-01 0.013810 0.013684 0.006549
10135 1980-03-01 0.053365 0.059318 0.061876
10136  
10137 Percentage of change in GOOG and APPL stock volume. Shows computing
10138 the percentage change between columns.
10139  
10140 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({
10141 ... '2016': [1769950, 30586265],
10142 ... '2015': [1500923, 40912316],
10143 ... '2014': [1371819, 41403351]},
10144 ... index=['GOOG', 'APPL'])
10145 >>> df
10146 2016 2015 2014
10147 GOOG 1769950 1500923 1371819
10148 APPL 30586265 40912316 41403351
10149  
10150 >>> df.pct_change(axis='columns', periods=-1)
10151 2016 2015 2014
10152 GOOG 0.179241 0.094112 NaN
10153 APPL -0.252395 -0.011860 NaN
10154 """
10155 axis = self._get_axis_number(kwargs.pop("axis", self._stat_axis_name))
10156 if fill_method is None:
10157 data = self
10158 else:
10159 _data = self.fillna(method=fill_method, axis=axis, limit=limit)
10160 assert _data is not None # needed for mypy
10161 data = _data
10162  
10163 shifted = data.shift(periods=periods, freq=freq, axis=axis, **kwargs)
10164 # Unsupported left operand type for / ("FrameOrSeries")
10165 rs = data / shifted - 1 # type: ignore[operator]
10166 if freq is not None:
10167 # Shift method is implemented differently when freq is not None
10168 # We want to restore the original index
10169 rs = rs.loc[~rs.index.duplicated()]
10170 rs = rs.reindex_like(data)
10171 return rs

10936 @final
10937 def _inplace_method(self, other, op):
10938 """
10939 Wrap arithmetic method to operate inplace.
10940 """
10941 result = op(self, other)
10942  
10943 if (
10944 self.ndim == 1
10945 and result._indexed_same(self)
10946 and is_dtype_equal(result.dtype, self.dtype)
10947 ):
10948 # GH#36498 this inplace op can _actually_ be inplace.
10949 self._values[:] = result._values
10950 return self
10951  
10952 # Delete cacher
10953 self._reset_cacher()
10954  
10955 # this makes sure that we are aligned like the input
10956 # we are updating inplace so we want to ignore is_copy
10957 self._update_inplace(
10958 result.reindex_like(self, copy=False), verify_is_copy=False
10959 )
10960 return self

11009 @final
11010 def _find_valid_index(self, *, how: str) -> Hashable | None:
11011 """
11012 Retrieves the index of the first valid value.
11013  
11014 Parameters
11015 ----------
11016 how : {'first', 'last'}
11017 Use this parameter to change between the first or last valid index.
11018  
11019 Returns
11020 -------
11021 idx_first_valid : type of index
11022 """
11023 idxpos = find_valid_index(self._values, how=how)
11024 if idxpos is None:
11025 return None
11026 return self.index[idxpos]

11122

11134 True, then the result will be {empty_value}, as for an empty row/column.
11135 If skipna is False, then NA are treated as True, because these are not
11136 equal to zero.

11153 _all_desc = """\
11154 Return whether all elements are True, potentially over an axis.
11155  
11156 Returns True unless there at least one element within a series or
11157 along a Dataframe axis that is False or equivalent (e.g. zero or
11158 empty)."""
11159  
11160 _all_examples = """\
11161 Examples
11162 --------
11163 **Series**
11164  
11165 >>> pd.Series([True, True]).all()
11166 True
11167 >>> pd.Series([True, False]).all()
11168 False
11169 >>> pd.Series([], dtype="float64").all()
11170 True
11171 >>> pd.Series([np.nan]).all()
11172 True
11173 >>> pd.Series([np.nan]).all(skipna=False)
11174 True
11175  
11176 **DataFrames**
11177  
11178 Create a dataframe from a dictionary.
11179  
11180 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'col1': [True, True], 'col2': [True, False]})
11181 >>> df
11182 col1 col2
11183 0 True True
11184 1 True False
11185  
11186 Default behaviour checks if column-wise values all return True.
11187  
11188 >>> df.all()
11189 col1 True
11190 col2 False
11191 dtype: bool
11192  
11193 Specify ``axis='columns'`` to check if row-wise values all return True.
11194  
11195 >>> df.all(axis='columns')
11196 0 True
11197 1 False
11198 dtype: bool
11199  
11200 Or ``axis=None`` for whether every value is True.
11201  
11202 >>> df.all(axis=None)
11203 False
11204 """
11205  
11206 _all_see_also = """\
11207 See Also
11208 --------
11209 Series.all : Return True if all elements are True.
11210 DataFrame.any : Return True if one (or more) elements are True.

11214 Return cumulative {desc} over a DataFrame or Series axis.
11215  
11216 Returns a DataFrame or Series of the same size containing the cumulative
11217 {desc}.
11218  
11219 Parameters
11220 ----------
11221 axis : {{0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}}, default 0
11222 The index or the name of the axis. 0 is equivalent to None or 'index'.
11223 skipna : bool, default True
11224 Exclude NA/null values. If an entire row/column is NA, the result
11225 will be NA.
11226 *args, **kwargs
11227 Additional keywords have no effect but might be accepted for

11230 Returns
11231 -------

11519 Return whether any element is True, potentially over an axis.
11520  
11521 Returns False unless there is at least one element within a series or

11525 _any_examples = """\
11526 Examples
11527 --------
11528 **Series**
11529  
11530 For Series input, the output is a scalar indicating whether any element
11531 is True.
11532  
11533 >>> pd.Series([False, False]).any()
11534 False
11535 >>> pd.Series([True, False]).any()
11536 True
11537 >>> pd.Series([], dtype="float64").any()
11538 False
11539 >>> pd.Series([np.nan]).any()
11540 False
11541 >>> pd.Series([np.nan]).any(skipna=False)
11542 True
11543  
11544 **DataFrame**
11545  
11546 Whether each column contains at least one True element (the default).
11547  
11548 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({"A": [1, 2], "B": [0, 2], "C": [0, 0]})
11549 >>> df
11550 A B C
11551 0 1 0 0
11552 1 2 2 0
11553  
11554 >>> df.any()
11555 A True
11556 B True
11557 C False
11558 dtype: bool
11559  
11560 Aggregating over the columns.
11561  
11562 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({"A": [True, False], "B": [1, 2]})
11563 >>> df
11564 A B
11565 0 True 1
11566 1 False 2
11567  
11568 >>> df.any(axis='columns')
11569 0 True
11570 1 True
11571 dtype: bool
11572  
11573 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({"A": [True, False], "B": [1, 0]})
11574 >>> df
11575 A B
11576 0 True 1
11577 1 False 0
11578  
11579 >>> df.any(axis='columns')
11580 0 True
11581 1 False
11582 dtype: bool
11583  
11584 Aggregating over the entire DataFrame with ``axis=None``.
11585  
11586 >>> df.any(axis=None)
11587 True
11588  
11589 `any` for an empty DataFrame is an empty Series.
11590  
11591 >>> pd.DataFrame([]).any()
11592 Series([], dtype: bool)

11690 min_count : int, default 0

11695  
11696 def _align_as_utc(
11697 left: FrameOrSeries, right: FrameOrSeries, join_index: Index | None
11698 ) -> tuple[FrameOrSeries, FrameOrSeries]:
11699 """
11700 If we are aligning timezone-aware DatetimeIndexes and the timezones
11701 do not match, convert both to UTC.
11702 """
11703 if is_datetime64tz_dtype(left.index.dtype):
11704 if left.index.tz != right.index.tz:
11705 if join_index is not None:
11706 # GH#33671 ensure we don't change the index on
11707 # our original Series (NB: by default deep=False)
11708 left = left.copy()
11709 right = right.copy()
11710 left.index = join_index
11711 right.index = join_index
11712  
11713 return left, right
